This version is nowhere near 400 lines, but does everything except
recall *exactly* a screenful:

    /set bg_output=off

    /def -p1 -ag -F -h'WORLD' world_recall = \
        /echo -- ---- world %1 ----%; 
        /let old_more=%more%;
        /set more=off%;
        /quote -S /echo -- `/recall /25%; 
        /set more=%old_more

By turning %more off, it can recall more than a screenful without causing
a --More-- prompt.  A few lines will scroll off the top, and you'll be
left with a screenful, and %more is restored to its original value.
One problem with this (and the 400 line version, at least as you described
it) is that you can't distinguish old recalled lines from new lines you
haven't seen yet.

In 3.5 beta 1, you will be able to replace the abitrary 25 used in the
above example with $[lines()], to get very close to exactly a screenful.

