Well, just as a suggestion to what your problem might be:

Xterm is a VT100 compatible terminal.

VT100 has a rather interesting little feature. Namely, if you place the cursor
at the very char character of a line and print/type one more character, it's
cursor wont move to the next line and leave a character at the last colomn of
the old row, as you might expect. Rather, it will print the character without
moving! Hince, if you press return following that, you'll get to the next
line. On a terminal that don't have this feature, you would already be on the
next line, and pressing return then will cause you to go one more line,
leaving you with an empty line. So, if you have text that goes beyond colomn
79 (assuming you have an 80 character display, and count characters  as 1-80)
and then adds a return, you will get different behaviour on different
terminals.

This would make it look correct in an xterm for example, but not on a FreeBSD
console, for example (since the FreeBSD console does not have the "stay put"-
feature). I don't know about the linux console. I thought it DID have that
feature, though. Hmm...

Oh well, just a suggestion... Look into it. Good luck.

