Last night in bed I had a brainstorm for a method (For those of you
familiar with the page extension common on TinyMUCK FuzzBall, and possibly
TinyMUCK 2.2/2.3 that allows custom formats) to hilight the from, to, and
body of a page, without needing to know the format the page will be in. 
The trick is you need to have a 'prepend' to the page that contains all
the info, then TF can catch that, strip it off, and set temporary hilights
on the guts of the page..  It works great... Once..  After that the string
gets really frotzed..  I think I may know what the problem is (I use
/substitute, then proceed to use data from the origonal match) If you
wanna play with it, pages need to be recieved in this format: ##PAGE>
fromname #<># to-list #><# Body <EGAP## Origonal format page here The
to-list is a list of names recieving the page (Such as Johnny, Fred and
you) Then the macro is:
/def -p1000 -F -mregexp \
-t'^##PAGE> ([^ ]+) #<># ([^ ]+((, [^ ]+)* and [^ ]+)?) #><# (.*) <EGAP##' \
catchpage = \
  /substitute %PR %; \
  /def -p999 -F -mregexp -t\"($(/escape \(\)\[\]\|\*\+\?\.\\ %P2))\" -P1Ccyan pageto %; \
  /def -p998 -F -mregexp -t\"($(/escape \(\)\[\]\|\*\+\?\.\\ %P5))\" -P1Cblue pagebody %; \
  /def -p997 -F -mregexp -t\"($(/escape \(\)\[\]\|\*\+\?\.\\ %P1))\" -P1Cyellow pagefrom = \
    /undef pageto %%; \
    /undef pagebody %%; \
    /undef pagefrom

Moving the /substitute to the end does indeed fix the problem.
