/repeat normally executes commands asynchronously; that means they are
not executed immediately, just scheduled to be executed later.  "Later"
might be 0 seconds later, but it is always _after_ anything directly
following the /repeat (<command2> in this case).

To execute the commands synchornously ("in-line"), use /repeat -S.

/help topics: /repeat, processes.

