Try this one out. I use it to filter out all Org (chat line) output in
AmberMUSH when logging. Just set the RegExp to catch all the output you 
_want_ in your log. This is best done by logically negating (ie. using
a leading '^' inside square brackets) the _unwanted_ output.
Just to make the example a little clearer: all Org output in AmberMUSH is 
preceeded by a '<' char. Changing the RegExp to match one or more complex
patterns should not be a problem.


/def -mregexp -p10 -F -t"^[^<]" = /echo -wAmberLog - %*
/def lon = /log -wAmberLog

/addworld AmberMUSH muds.okstate.edu 5150
/addworld AmberLog dummy dummy


Now activate selective logging with '/lon'.

The trigger /echos all sanctioned output to a dummy world (in this case
'AmberLog') and logs from there. Simple, although it is a bit roundabout.

Note: In general, the /def should be set to a higher priority than all 
non-fallthrough output triggers to insure that it will be checked once 
for each line.


