Hi all,

There's been a few messages about random actions lately, I thought I'd
share the method I came up with.  It takes advantage of tf's method of
calling a random trigger when they have the same text and priority.
Combine this witht the repeat command and you can have your characters
doing things, seemingly at random.

First create several triggers that do the random actions you'd like to
choose from.  Here's a quick example:

/def -t'random_bored' = stretch
/def -t'random_bored' = yawn
/def -t'random_bored' = sigh

These all have the same trigger text and are the same priority.

Next, issue a repeat command to call one of the triggers at random,
like so:

/repeat -10 99999 /if (rand(100)<25) /trigger random_bored;/endif

What this does is, every 10 seconds, there is a 25% chance that you
will perforn a random bored action.  You can adjuct the frequency and
percent chance to your likiing, depending on what you are trying to
do.  You can expand this and create other macros to set 'bored' mode,
etc.  If you are running multiple worlds at the same time, just use
the -w parameters to limit it to the specific world.

Comments and suggested enhancements would be appreciated.

