Ok... a few asked, so this is how one MIGHT run tf automagically from cron.

Type in the following script:

#!/bin/sh
if ! ps -x|grep -w tf|grep -v grep > /dev/null 2>&1
then
  exec tf < /dev/null > /dev/null
fi

Save it to a file... say we call it "check_tf".  do a chmod u+x check_tf to 
make it executable.  Then either create your self a crontab file (say called 
my_crontab) or add a line such as

	*/5 * * * * (directory where check_tf is located)/check_tf

This means check every 5 minutes.  If you want it to be more often or less 
often, change the "5" to another number.

Then do a 

	crontab my_crontab

Now... the above makes a few assumptions.

	1) You are using a BSDish unix.  If not the "ps" command may take different parameters.  Under SysVish unixes, it's probably going to be ps -e, but you should check your local man page.
	2) Your sysadmin hasn't disable cron.  A few don't run cron daemons because they feel you shouldn't be sucking processor cycles if you aren't logged in.
	3) You particular crontab file format and utilities may be different, so read the man page and double check.
	4) You tf bot requires NO input and you don't want to see any of the output.  Cron jobs are not bound to a terminal, so you can't send them input from the keyboard or read the output on your screen.  If you need to give it input or read the output you'll have to change what file is being used as input ( the file being redirected into the program with the "<" sign) and the file used as output ( the ">" redirected file )

Nonetheless, this should give you an idea of what ya need to do.  Hope this helps.

			-Ben Greenwald


