> This is what I need. I need to define a trigger that defines a trigger.
> 
> Take a look:
> /def -mregexp -p2 -F -t'You are hungry' = \
>   /if (PARTAL =/ "Yes") \
>     /send eat partial%;\
>   /else \
>     /set CASTING=Yes%;\
>     /alias_food%;\
>     /def -mregexp -p2 -F -n1 -t'You complete your spell' = \
>       /send get ration%;\
>       /send eat ration%;\
>       /RestMagic%;\
>   /endif%;
> 
> 
> The problem is that I think the secon trigger is taking the endif with it.

The inner /def ends at the "%;" after "get ration".  "eat ration" is
part of the outer /else, not the inner /def.  When you nest evaluations
(i.e., /def or /eval), you need to use %% and $$ to produce literal %
and $ in the nested code.  Thus:

  /def -mregexp -p2 -F -t'You are hungry' = \
    /if (PARTAL =/ "Yes") \
      /send eat partial%;\
    /else \
      /set CASTING=Yes%;\
      /alias_food%;\
      /def -mregexp -p2 -F -n1 -t'You complete your spell' = \
        /send get ration%%;\
        /send eat ration%%;\
        /RestMagic%;\
    /endif%;

