Phil Geer wrote:
> 
> I have been using the stack_queue.tf library file to hold lists of items.
> I would prefer to have an array (C) or record (pascal) data structure to
> hold things like Skill scores and items, prices.  how can I do this?

Generate variable names on the fly, using /eval to evaluate the generated
code.  For example, the definition

    /def echo_array = \
        /let arrayname=%{1}%;\
        /let index=1%;\
        /while /test %{arrayname}__%{index} !~ ""%; /do \
            /eval /echo %%{%{arrayname}__%{index}}%;\
            /test index := index + 1%;\
        /done

will enable you to call "/echo_array inventory" to echo the values of
the variables inventory__1, inventory__2, inventory__3, etc.  This
example illustrates an open-ended array, but fixed-sized arrays and
structures can be implemented with the same technique.

Note that /test evaluates its arguments, which is why no /eval was
needed in the /while condition.  Using the abbreviated condition
syntax, it would have been necessary to /eval the entire /while
statement and escape the %'s it contains:

    /def echo_array = \
        /let arrayname=%{1}%;\
        /let index=1%;\
        /eval \
            /while (%{arrayname}__%{index} !~ "") \
                /eval /echo %%%{%%{arrayname}__%%{index}}%%;\
                /test index := index + 1%%;\
            /done

