	You probably don't want those %'s inside of the if () check,
because if () already does that.  Also, only have one set of ()'s in the
regexp, so P2 is empty.

	I also have no idea what /wait is, but you didn't put a %; after
it.  If it is a macro which executes the rest of it's arguments after
the time period (ie. /wait TIME STUFF...), then you need to double the
nested %'s.  I'll assume this is what it is, although it seems a bit
strange:

/def wait = /repeat -%1 1 %-1

/def -mregexp -p1 -t"^\[ INFO \] ([A-Z][a-z]+) has LEVELED!!!!!!$" leveled =\
    /if ({P1} !~ "Lightn") \
	/let t=$[rand(1, 5)]%;\
	/wait $[rand(5, 10)]\
	    /if (%t == 1) grats Way to go %{P1}!%%;\
	    /elseif (%t == 2) grats Alright %{P1}!!%%;\
	    /elseif (%t == 3) grats Go %{P1}!%%;\
	    /elseif (%t == 4) grats Good Job %{P1}!%%;\
	    /else grats %{P1}!!%%;\
	    /endif%;\
    /endif

Note that I didn't double % the P1's and that I didn't follow the rule
above about not needing the % in the if.  WHY?  Because with your /wait
(/repeat), the local variables t and P1 will be gone before the macro
runs, so we substitute the values in now ahead of time.  Currently
you're safe with the regexp you use for names, but if you let people
have names like '%;/quit' they'd be able to control your tf, by setting
to a tricky name and leveling.

	You might just want to do:

/def -mregexp -p1 -t"^\[ INFO \] ([A-Z][a-z]+) has LEVELED!!!!!!$" leveled =\
    /if ({P1} !~ "Lightn") \
	/let t=$[rand(1, 5)]%;\
	/let w=$[rand(5, 10)]%;\
	/if (t == 1) /wait %w grats Way to go %{P1}!%%;\
	/elseif (t == 2) /wait %w grats Alright %{P1}!!%%;\
	/elseif (t == 3) /wait %w grats Go %{P1}!%%;\
	/elseif (t == 4) /wait %w grats Good Job %{P1}!%%;\
	/else /wait %w grats %{P1}!!%%;\
	/endif%;\
    /endif

And make sure your /wait is defined safely as:

/def wait = /repeat -%1 1 $(/escape \\% %-1)

