Once upon a time you, Christopher T. Walker, wrote:
> 
> Someone wanna tell me the code to bind the F1-F12 keys. I'm too lazy to
> read and look it up. Sorry.
> 
> Anyone Know?

You had best sort it out yourself, since it depends on the system you are
using.

So F1 can be either ^[[[A (eg Linux), ^[[M (eg FreeBSD), ^[OP (eg SunOS),
^[[11~ (eg DOS). In most cases F2-F4 are defined "following" F1, but
F5-F10 and F11, F12 are usually completely different.

On most systems, typing Ctrl-V followed by the function key, will show
the escape code for this key.

You can set up your bindings like

/def -b^[[[A F1 = code for F1 key binding.

Johan.

P.S. Do not define keybindings F1-F12 for all systems at the same time:
	they can - and usually will - clash.


