	You have a couple problems.  The /for is going to cause some
tricks, just because you really have to think about all of the double
quoting inside.

	The $(/eval /echo tg%{x}) is the same as $(/echo tg%{x}).  What
you want to do is move the /eval out a lot.  Using /eval basically tells
tf to do another set of % and $ expansions.  So to look at %{tg%{id}}
(which is what you want to get to).  You can do something like:

/def foo=\
    /eval /echo %%{tg%{idd}}

When you type /foo, % and $ subs are filled in.  (assuming idd is 1)
/eval /echo %{tg1}

Then the /eval goes and does another set of % and $ subs:
(assuming tg1 = 10)
/echo 10


So in your example, you'd be wanting to do something more like:
/eval /echo Target %%{idd} is %%{tg%{idd}}

Note that I use double %'s on the first idd.  Since we know idd is just
a number (in this case) it's not too big of a deal.  However, if idd was
a string that had some '%'s in it itself then you don't want to eval
that stuff.  Make sense?


Your addtarg macro doesn't need a /eval at all, so don't use it.  About
the only time you ever need to use /eval is when you are doing
''double-variable'' kinds of things.

I'm not sure why you use idd in your ltargs macro at all, so I'm going
to take it out, and use the 'i' of the for loop.

/set id=0
/def addtarg =\
    /set tg%{id}=%1%;\
    /set id=$[id+1]

/def ltargs=\
    /echo *** targets ***%;\
    /for i 0 $[id-1] \
        /eval /echo Target %%%{i} is  %%%{tg%%{i}}

Note the extra set of %'s in the /for just because /for is actually a
macro, not a builtin command (/list -i for).


Tested in tf35a18.

