/dokey LNEXT (default ^V) is a tf feature, chosen to follow unix
conventions.  It will work to quote (avoid interpreting) the next
chracter received by tf.  However, under unix shells (I don't know
about OS/2), the interrupt, quit, and suspend characters (usually ^C,
^\, and ^Z) are intercepted by the terminal driver before they reach
tf.  The terminal driver sends the corresponding signal (SIGINT,
SIGQUIT, or SIGTSTP) to tf.  Since tf never receives the keystroke, tf
can't do anything with it.

Under unix, you can use stty to change or disable those special keys
so they won't be intercepted by the terminal driver, and tf will
receive them.  But it will then become difficult to generate those
signals.  You could do:

  /def -b^C = /signal INT
  /def -b^\ = /signal QUIT
  /def -b^Z = /signal TSTP

But unlike the signals generated by the terminal driver, those signals
will be generated synchronously with other tf commands.  This means
when you type one of those characters, any macro that is currently
running must finish before tf will process the character.  This will
probably not be a problem for ^Z, but it makes ^C lose the ability to
interrupt an out-of-control macro.

