I myself work a lot on line based 3270 telnet (IBM mainframe) and have 
figured out that it's quite possible to work with character based 
programs, as long as you keep a few things in mind. Every character on 
the line is sent as a character, so if you send a sequence of characters 
you send a sequence of single characters (sounds logical, doesn't it ;) 
This is so logical, that working from that you can perfectly figure out 
what to do with a character oriented editor (take for example, emacs. It 
has a function that reads a file, ^X^F filename). This can be perfectly 
done with a line oriented telnet, as follows: You type the line as being:
^X^Ffilename.c<enter>
This will invoke the load-file command in emacs, and send the filename 
after it and a return. This will perfectly load the file. Going 10 lines 
down can be done as follows: ^N^N^N^N^N^N^N^N^N^N
The only problem here is, is that the enter will be sent as an actual 
enter. This will create an empty line. To delete this, you have ti 
prepend ^K^K to your next command line.

Also, if you know how to navigate through certain programs, you can use 
the keycodes for that (eg: to quit 'pine' a mailreader, you send 'qyy')

This only works for things where you can either easilly void the 'extra' 
behaviour of the enter key, or you can rewrite a little of the tf-code to 
not let it send a CR when you hit enter, but make it so that you have to 
use a different key to send a literal enter.

