I don't know about other people, but I have written a few source-level
hacks for tf, to do various things. However, I recently upgraded to the
Debian packaged version, and so of course lost all my modifications.

This, in itself, is not a problem; I can always put them back into this
version. The problem comes with some of the code which I've written in my
.tfrc etc, which uses some of the features I added, and which is now
broken. So, I thought to myself, `why don't I put in some mechanism to
allow the code to work out what was in the version it was running on, and
act accordingly?'

The sort of thing I have in mind goes something like:
  o  Somebody implements something groovy that requires a source-code
     modification.
  o  To the patch, they add a line which inserts something into one of the
     header files or source files, indicating the presence of this code.
     This is probably the trickiest bit. The easiest way seems to be to
     define a macro `ADD_FEATURE(name)', which adds it somehow to a global
     list, but this is probably hackish. However, getting patch to insert
     a line into a list sounds quite annoying too ... :(
  o  Any support code they write, or any code anyone else writes, can use
     the hasfeature(name) function to check if the named feature is
     present, and behave (eg not load) accordingly.

So, there are a few questions. One: is this a good idea, or should I just
be lobbying Hawkeye to get them included in the mainstream
distribution[1]? :)

Two: can anybody think of a better way of doing it?

Three: should I try for some way of allowing you to include version
numbers etc (featureversion(name))?

This is still very much speculative, but any comments would be
appreciated.

Cheers!

&E

