My dear Myrddin,
You couldn't be more wrong. If a process is taking 97% CPU on a UNIX
machine, it is simply using all the CPU it could possibly get. The last
few percent is probably the system itself that is using. Normally, my TFs
are using about 0.00% CPU on my FreeBSD system, running on a P75. Notice
that top itself, which displays these numbers actually took a LOT more.
In a UNIX enviroment, programs don't take all the CPU they get, unless
they are malfunctioning, or doing very heavy calculations, or so.
In DOS they do. There you just sit and wait, eating CPU, while waiting for
user input, or so. In UNIX you tell the system you want data and sit down
nicely and wait, giving CPU to other things. If there is no other program
to run, the CPU will sit and wait in the systems idleloop function.
Something is very wrong if TF is eating 99% CPU, because TF is very well
behaved and would do so only if:
1) There is something wrong with the system (could be)
2) Alice has configured some tiggers or hooks that are looking or otherwise
   not doing what was probably intended to.

