Most of the time, tf should just be waiting for input from the user
or a server; while it waits, it gives up control of the cpu.  But
there are several ways tf could be made to do a lot of work during
those times it should normally be idle:

  Unwisely running nontrivial tf processes (/quote or /repeat) with
  -0 or %ptime=0.

  Unwisely running highly recursive or iterative macros, especially if
  %max_recur or %max_iter has been increased.

  An obscure bug in tf or your OS uncovered by using an unusual
  combination of input and time related features: /quote, /repeat,
  input from server, %refreshtime, %prompt_sec, %prompt_usec,
  %maildelay, %ptime.

Without more information about what you're doing, I can't tell you what
your problem is.  You can narrow it down by systematically avoiding
your normal operations: e.g., start with "tf -f <host> <port>" to skip
any possible problems related to your normal startup files, and see how
tf behaves then.

