"Phil Geer" <pjgeer@MailBox.Syr.Edu> writes:

>     Someone said that tf has to check every line of output from the world
> against every trigger loaded.  If there are a whole bunch of triggers
> loaded, will it slow down tf significantly?  Is it a good idea to purge
> triggers when I'm done with them?  What is the right way to go about this,
> with /undef?  Will this free up memory or in any way make tf run
> better/faster?  What about /set and /unset, does /unset free up memory or
> otherwise help tf run better?

	It is unlikely to slow down tf very much unless you are on a
slow machine to begin with.  You can also help by making using 'more
specific' triggers, like avoiding leading '*' with glob or using lots of
'.*' with regexps.  But again those shouldn't matter much unless it's
pretty slow.  If you really are done with the triggers you can use
/undef if they are named (naming triggers is always a smart idea).
/unset'ing a variable is unlikely to reduce the amount of memory being
used.  If you think you are using a lot of memory, you could lower the
amount of history (/help histsize).

	Now if you do have a lot of triggers, and do want them always
around, you can make things run a little faster by setting priorities on
them such that more common triggers have higher priority.  This way tf
shouldn't have to check quite as many triggers per line of mud text.


