> I had a similar problem when I used /watch. I had set watch on about 20 
> of my friends and it started going really slow. When I removed them 
> things ran faster again so I'd say, don't use too many triggers, 
> especially if they are set to be activated on time.

	The problem with the watch command isn't the triggers, it's that
for each person you are watching, tf sends a 'WHO' to the mud every 60
seconds.  So you were averaging sending 'WHO' every 3 seconds and then
doing a wee bit of trigger matching on that.  /watch normally has 0
triggers installed.  When it's actively processing the WHO list, it'll
install 3 temporarily until the of the list.  So even with 20 of them
installed, at most you only have 3 extra triggers at any given time, and
usually no extra.

	For those inclined, /watch can be easily rewritten to only send
one WHO per minute no matter how many people you are waiting on, and
without using more triggers than a single /watch.


