On Sat, 16 Nov 1996, Phil Geer wrote:

> I am trying to make a trigger that quits me out when someone suddenly
> attacks me, other than the mob i am currently battling.
> 
> Here is what i have:
> /set playername=Phil
> /set target=a harmless flea
> /eval /def -1 -t'^(^%{target}) hit %{playername}' danger1 = quit
>                   ^^^^^^^^^^^^
> I'm pretty sure that part is wrong.

Yes, I think you're probably right. :) The '^' character can be used in
regular expressions either within square brackets, to provide negation, or
to mark the beginning of the line.

Instead, you can define a trigger with a higher priority, which does not
fall through (ie, don't use the -F switch to /def), and which matches just
your special case(s). Then your original trigger will not get to see `a
harmless flea hit phil.' This works fine in most cases, but if you're trying
to define a one-shot trigger, you may run into problems; probably the
easiest way is to name your override, and get the other trigger to remove
it, as follows:
      
	/eval /def -t'^%{target} hit %{playername}' danger1_ovr
	/eval /def -t'hit %{playername}' -1 danger1 = quit%%; /undef danger1_ovr

But note that, both in this case and with the one given above, you can't use
these in more than one world at a time, cos the triggers will replace each
other. However, you can use the ``special substitution'' ${world_name} to
name each trigger by the world you are CURRENTLY IN. But while we're at it,
if you are going to accept this restriction, we might as well use
${world_character} as well, to save you having to give your character name
seperately, as follows:

	/eval /def -t'^%{target} hit ${world_character}' \
		danger1_${world_name}_ovr
	/eval /def -t'hit ${world_character}' -1 danger1_${world_name} = \
		quit%%; /undef danger1_${world_name}_ovr
		
Obviously, since this is not the easiest thing to type in the middle of a
fight, you may prefer to define a macro to do this for you, but I'm sure you
can work that out for yourself! :)

So there you go. I hope this is (a) helpful, and (b) right ...

