> 
> $(for i 1 value /echo stuff) and somewhere in stuff is a $[rand(n)]
> 
> It gives me the same number each time. Is there a way I can tell it to
> evaluate the rand for each loop, not just once for the whole for?

	Quote tf expands the $[rand(n)] before it even starts the $(),
so you want to delay that expansion by quoting the $[].  You also have
to quote the ()'s inside of the rand in this case, so that the close
parenthesis doesn't match the one for $().

/def foo = /echo $(/for i 1 10 /echo \$[rand\(100\)])

/foo --> 97 59 26 53 70 0 60 43 33 30

Or
/def bar = /echo $[rand(100)]
/def foo = /echo $(/for i 1 10 /bar)

/foo --> 78 68 33 57 4 22 16 16 40 9


