It is possible to write a /pause that suspends the entire tf process,
but not one that suspends only the calling macro.  This violates the
usual nonblocking nature of tf, but if you don't mind blocking the
entire tf session, you can use this (assuming a unix shell):

    /def pause = /quote -S -decho !sleep %*

Note that if you do anything before the /pause (even /echo), it will execute
before the /pause, but you will not see the results until after the /pause.


