/set is okay, but /let is better: it creates local variables.
>     /set INDEX=2%;   \
>     /set DRAG=drag%; \
>     /set DRAG=$[strcat(%{DRAG}, " ", %{ITM})]%; \
If the server accepts a leading space, this can be handled by the loop.
The $[strcat...] is okay, but simple expansion is easier.
>     /while ($[%{INDEX} <= %{CNT}]) \
Don't use $[...] inside /while(...).
Don't use %{...} inside expressions (they work, but it's easier not to).
>        /set DRAG=$[strcat(%{DRAG}, " drag ", %{INDEX}, ".", %{ITM})]%; \
Again, the $[strcat...] is okay, but simple expansion is easier.
>        /set INDEX=$[INDEX + {1}]%; \
You want the number 1, not the first argument {1}.
>     /done%; \
>     /set DRAG=$[strcat(%{DRAG}, " ", %{DIR})]%; \
Again, the $[strcat...] is okay, but simple expansion is easier.
>     /send %{DRAG}

/def drag = \
    /let DIR=%{3}%;\
    /let ITEM=%{2}%;\
    /let CNT=%{1}%;\
    /let INDEX=1%;\
    /let DRAG=drag %{INDEX}.%{ITEM}%;\
    /while (INDEX <= CNT) \
       /let DRAG=%{DRAG} drag %{INDEX}.%{ITEM}%;\
       /let INDEX=$[INDEX + 1]%;\
    /done%;\
    /send - %{DRAG} %{DIR}

See the /help topics:  expansion, expressions, /while.

